<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,505,840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">
Three known species of this genus are endemic to southern 
<collectingCountry box="[873,938,505,531]" name="Chile" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Chile</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[998,1121,505,531]" name="Argentina" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. They are relatively large, heavily sclerotised, somewhat clerid-like beetles, dorsally clothed with scattered long setae and with 
<number box="[1396,1428,544,570]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="10.0">10</number>
- segmented antennae bearing a two-segmented antennal club (but with antennomere 
<number box="[1164,1179,582,608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="9.0">9</number>
narrower than 
<number box="[1364,1396,582,608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="10.0">10</number>
, so that the club may appear to be 
<number box="[519,528,621,647]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="1.0">1</number>
-segmented, 
<figureCitation box="[686,769,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1640,1664]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,879,1596]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,879,1617]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Adult habitus, dorsal. 1. Acalanthis semimetallica (Fairmaire &amp; Germain); 2. A. mirabilis Reitter; 3. A. quadrisignata Erichson; 4. Necrobiopsis shangrila sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275088/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[783,800,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 9. 5" captionStartId="6.[151,271,1772,1796]" captionTargetBox="[199,1401,196,1728]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,167,1773]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 9. 5. Necrobiopsis shangrila sp. nov., antenna; 6. Acalanthis mirabilis Reitter, antenna; 7. Necrobiopsis shangrila, front tibia; 8. N. shangrila, aedeagus dorsal; 9. Same, apex of aedeagus, showing parameres." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/275089/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">6</figureCitation>
). This genus was redescribed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kolibac" box="[1197,1377,619,647]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" refString="Kolibac, J. (2005) A review of the Trogisitidae. Part 1: Morphology of the genera (Coleoptera, Cleroidea). Entomologica Basiliensia et Collectionis Frey, 27, 39 - 159." type="journal article" year="2005">
Kolibáč (
<number box="[1307,1369,621,647]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="2005.0">2005</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
who illustrated the hind wing and mouth parts, but his illustration of the antenna (Pl. 
<number box="[1089,1104,660,686]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="1.0">1</number>
, fig. 
<number box="[1166,1181,660,686]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="5.0">5</number>
) is clearly wrong and belongs to a taxon of Trogossitinae.
</paragraph>
