<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,505,840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName box="[198,324,737,762]" class="Insecta" family="Trogossitidae" genus="Acalanthis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[198,324,737,762]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Acalanthis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Crowson" authorityName="Crowson" box="[553,836,737,763]" class="Insecta" family="Trogossitidae" genus="Paracalanthis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[553,719,737,762]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Paracalanthis</emphasis>
Crowson
</taxonomicName>
described from southern Queensland (Lamington National Park) but is distinguished by a lack of a spine on external margin of hind tibia and a sparser clothing of long setae. The antennal club in 
<taxonomicName box="[563,729,815,840]" class="Insecta" family="Trogossitidae" genus="Paracalanthis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[563,729,815,840]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="39">Paracalanthis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also more clearly 
<number box="[972,981,814,840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="39" value="1.0">1</number>
-segmented.
</paragraph>
